  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_6903568" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/6903568" />
    <a title="Christy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/248667-christy"><img alt="Christy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550952681p2/248667.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/6903568?book_show_action=true">Sep 27, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christy" href="/user/show/248667-christy">Christy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/248667-christy?shelf=african-american-lit-and-history">african-american-lit-and-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/248667-christy?shelf=readinglist1">readinglist1</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/248667-christy?shelf=20th-century-american-lit">20th-century-american-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer6903568" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer324831932480586496">Margaret Walker&apos;s novel <i>Jubilee</i> (1966), based on the life story of her great-grandmother, follows Vyry (This name is short for Elvira, which I only mention because her name puzzled me for 75% of the book until her full name was revealed.) from her birth as a slave in pre-Civil War Georgia through the Civil War and into the Reconstruction era in Georgia and Alabama. <br/><br/>Walker uses Vyry to represent African American experience in the generation or two before the twentieth century begins: Vyry is a sl</span>
  <span id="freeText324831932480586496" style="display:none">Margaret Walker's novel <i>Jubilee</i> (1966), based on the life story of her great-grandmother, follows Vyry (This name is short for Elvira, which I only mention because her name puzzled me for 75% of the book until her full name was revealed.) from her birth as a slave in pre-Civil War Georgia through the Civil War and into the Reconstruction era in Georgia and Alabama. <br /><br />Walker uses Vyry to represent African American experience in the generation or two before the twentieth century begins: Vyry is a slave (generally treated relatively well because she is a house slave); she tries to run away and is beaten and left for dead; she watches her master's family die during the Civil War; she stays with the remnants after the war as long as she can; she marries and moves away from Georgia when the last of the master's family leaves; they get flooded; they get caught by the trap of sharecropping; they have their home burned down by the Klan; they finally find a nice home; and her son Jim is able to go away to school, to Selma, gesturing toward the future of the race in the final pages of the book. <br /><br />However, Walker's attempt at such wide coverage falls flat. This is perhaps in part because there is little of Vyry's internal state throughout the book. Walker maintains a focus on external occurrences instead of providing a more personal sense of how this feels for Vyry. The distance that this creates between reader and character is exacerbated when, in the middle section of the book that covers the Civil War years, Vyry is all but forgotten as Walker details the experiences of the Dutton family (for whom Vyry is a slave) and their losses during the war.<br /><br />One way in which the broad scope of the novel does work is in its sympathetic coverage of the Dutton family during the war. While this coverage is a distraction from Vyry's experience, which is otherwise the focus of the book, it does make it possible to see white Southerners as human and not as the monsters that it would be all too easy to portray them as. Human and even well-intentioned though they may be, they are tremendously flawed, and Walker's novel is very clear about both elements.<br /><br />Ultimately, Walker's novel tells a story of hope. Despite the hardships of slavery, the war, and reconstruction, Vyry ends this story looking forward in love and anticipation of better days to come. Vyry is not a separatist but instead argues for a larger sense of community. <br /><br />She says at one point, "I couldn't tell you the name of the man what whipped me, and if I could it wouldn't make no difference. I honestly believes that if airy one of them peoples what treated me like dirt when I was a slave would come to my door in the morning hungry, I would feed em. God knows I ain't got no hate in my heart for nobody. If I is and doesn't know it, I prays to God to take it out. I ain't got no time to be hating. I believes in God and I believes in trying to love and help everybody, and I knows that humble is the way. I doesn't care what you calls me, that's my doctrine and I'm gwine to preach it to my childrens, every living one I got or ever hopes to have" (485).<br /><br />This generosity is moving and admirable. But is it an appropriate political response to violence, hatred, and disenfranchisement? Given the conflicts of the time period of the novel's narrative (Reconstruction, Jim Crow) and the conflicts of the time period of the publication of the novel (segregation, bussing, Civil Rights), it seems far too simple. Just be nice to people and they'll be nice to you sounds nice enough, but, as Randall points out, not everyone lives by that philosophy and thus there has to be more to the movement for freedom and equality than hope and niceness.</span>
  <a data-text-id="324831932480586496" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

